        {
            "author_association": "MEMBER",
            "body": "I understand the concern about \"AI slop\" but let's try to go about this in a reasonable way. Not to be the tone policer but talks like the \"codebase is polluted with garbage\" or that things need to be \"purified\" as part of the issue tracker worry me. that sort of language in a work setting usually do not lead anywhere good (as opposed to just crashing out on social media on a Friday night, which I admit also is part of my past times)\n\nWe are not going to _break_ git history over one-liner fixes any day and probably not for larger \"contaminations\" either. it is not like CLA/DCO-heavy Professional codebases typically make exceptions for these kind of sm0l fixes as well (are they even copyrightable in the first place). \n\nIf there is a concern that \"AI slop style\" has leaked into code comments, that can be fixed by submitting follow up PR:s that improve or removes such comments if they are redundant (`git blame` works, not every slightly messy numeric check needs to contain embedded comments).\n\n\n",
