        {
            "author_association": "MEMBER",
            "body": "> I know the United States has definitively stated (and had upheld by the courts) that anything output by an LLM(be it code, \"art\", a novel, etc.) cannot be copyrighted.\n\nThere were also cases in other countries - e.g. in Germany: https://www.gesetze-bayern.de/Content/Document/Y-300-Z-BECKRS-B-2026-N-1513?hl=true\nBut with a bit more nuance: It depends to what degree a Human shaped the result whether it can be copyright protected or not. So the statement that _any_ LLM use means you can't have copyright on the result doesn't appear to be entirely true.\nWe'd probably need input from an actual copyright law expert to have confirmation that taking on commits like that is (un)problematic.\n\nThat said - I don't like the direction things are going either",
