        {
            "author_association": "NONE",
            "body": "@bfredl @clason \n\nIn any other case I can think of, I would agree with you! Aiming for \"purity\" and performing \"purges\" are no better in software than they are in the real world. As for my statement about people intentionally ceasing to use projects that incorporate LLM-generated code, this is a literal fact. I'm not trying to bully neovim or anyone else, merely trying to point out that this is truly seen as a very large issue by a number of people. I'm not saying that thousands of neovim users specifically are leaving; I'm just pointing out that there are thousands of people across the whole planet that are committed to such a path.\n\nI truly do appreciate all the hard work that has gone into neovim; I've been a happy user for many, many years. I would like to see the project continue for even longer. One key thing everyone seems to keep skipping over (presumably because of my poor presentation) is that _regardless of code quality_ my issue with the use of LLMs is that they are naturally unethical. I have said this multiple times, but everyone keeps going back to code quality, maintainer load, or other side topics that are irrelevant until that main issue is addressed.\n\nI am here begging for what respite might be found to spare a project that is a daily part of my life from using inherently unethical devices. Nothing more, nothing less.\n\nI'll stop bugging y'alls; it really hasn't been my intention to bully, shame, harass, or otherwise cause for an unpleasant interaction. I truly just want to get across how big of an issue this is seen in the wider community.",
